  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Comfort",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The manner in which Paul, so to speak, fondles this word, is most beautiful. Compare 2 Corinthians 1:4-6.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "The manner in which Paul, so to speak, fondles this word, is most beautiful. Compare ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Corinthians 1:4-6",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Mourning (ὀδυρμόν)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Only here and Matthew 2:18. It implies a verbal expression of grief. Cebes, a disciple of Socrates, in his Pinax represents Λύπη Lupe, Sorrow, as a woman, with her head bowed upon her breast; Ὁδύνη Odune, consuming Grief, follows, tearing her hair. By her side is Ὁδυρμός Odurmos, Lamentation, a revolting, emaciated figure, whose sister is Ἁθυμία Athumia, Despondency. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Only here and ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Matthew 2:18",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". It implies a verbal expression of grief. Cebes, a disciple of Socrates, in his Pinax represents Λύπη Lupe, Sorrow, as a woman, with her head bowed upon her breast; Ὁδύνη Odune, consuming Grief, follows, tearing her hair. By her side is Ὁδυρμός Odurmos, Lamentation, a revolting, emaciated figure, whose sister is Ἁθυμία Athumia, Despondency. ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
